  "text": "The fact that inhibition occurred specifically when the motion detection task was perceptually demanding concurs with another line of research on the interactions of task demands and attention (e.g., [CITATION_1] [CITATION_2] . Here we show that this interaction is feature specific, in agreement with [CITATION_3] , who found effects of feature-based attention when the attended stimuli were presented together with distractors. In addition, our results suggest task demands have an inhibitory influence. Similar feature-specific task demands are also consistent with [CITATION_4] finding that a linguistically demanding task reduces functional responses to motion; and featurespecific task demands might explain the seeming contradiction that [CITATION_5] observed attentional costs of an (incongruent) working memory task on contour perception, while others found that during visual search (in the absence of an incongruent task) such contours do not require much attention but pop out [CITATION_6] [CITATION_7] .",
